l. 4, US Government Printing Office, 1870 {{oclc|752259860}}.\n* Nahin, Paul J., ''Oliver Heaviside: The Life, Work, and Times of an Electrical Genius of the Victorian Age'', Johns Hopkins University Press, 2002 {{ISBN|9780801869099}}.\n* Orji, Uchenna Jerome, ''International Telecommunications Law and Policy'', Cambridge Scholars Publishing, 2019 {{ISBN|9781527526419}}.\n* Parsons, Patrick R., ''Blue Skies: A History of Cable Television'', Temple University Press, 2008 {{ISBN|1592137067}}\n* Pitt, Douglas C., ''The Telecommunications Function of the British Post Office'', Saxon House, 1980 {{ISBN|9780566002731}}.\n* Prescott, George Bartlett, ''History, Theory, and Practice of the Electric Telegraph'', Boston: Ticknor and Fields, 1866 {{LCCN|17010907}}\n* Roberts, Steven, [http://distantwriting.co.uk/index.htm ''Distant Writing''], distantwriting.co.uk,\n** ch. 4, \"The Electric Telegraph Company\", [https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/en/archive/20160107230519/http://distantwriting.co.uk/electrictelegraphcompany.html archived] 1 July 2016,\n** ch. 5, \"Competitors and allies\", [https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/en/archive/20160107230155/http://distantwriting.co.uk/competitorsallies.html archived] 1 July 2016.\n* Russell, Robert W., [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=k6xGAQAAMAAJ ''History of the Invention of the Electric Telegraph''], New York: William C. Bryant & Co., 1853 {{oclc|904216191}}.\n* Schiffer, Michael B., ''Power Struggles: Scientific Authority and the Creation of Practical Electricity Before Edison'', MIT Press, 2008 {{ISBN|9780262195829}}.\n* Seward, Ingrid, ''The Queen's Speech: An Intimate Portrait of the Queen in Her Own Words'', Simon and Schuster, 2015 {{ISBN|1471150976}}.\n* [[Taliaferro Preston Shaffner|Shaffner, Taliaferro Preston]], [https://archive.org/stream/telegraphmanualc00shafrich#page/n3/mode/2up ''The Telegraph Manual''], Pudney & Russell, 1859.\n* [[Willoughby Smith|Smith, Willoughby]], [https://archive.org/details/riseandextensio00smitgoog ''The Rise and Extension of Submarine Telegraphy''], London:  J.S. Virtue & Co., 1891 {{oclc|1079820592}}.\n* Stephenson, Charles, ''The Fortifications of Malta 1530\u20131945'', Bloomsbury Publishing, 2012 {{ISBN|9781849080156}}.\n* Thomas, William Arthur, ''The Provincial Stock Exchanges'', Routledge, 2012 {{ISBN|9780714629810}} (1973 reprint).\n* [[Silvanus P. Thompson|Thompson, Silvanus Phillips]], ''The Life of Lord Kelvin'', vol. 1, American Mathematical Society, 2004 {{ISBN|9780821837436}} (first published 1910).\n* Walker, Peter M., \"Contract\", ''The Solicitors' Journal'', vol. 142, 1998.\n* Welch, Dick; Fr\u00e9mond, Olivier (eds), ''The Case-by-case Approach to Privatization'', World Bank Publications, 1998 {{ISBN|9780821341964}}.\n* Wenzlhuemer, Roland, ''Connecting the Nineteenth-Century World: The Telegraph and Globalization'', Cambridge University Press, 2013 {{ISBN|1107025281}}.\n* Williams, Liz, ''Kind Regards: The Lost Art of Letter Writing'', Michael O'Mara Books, 2012 {{ISBN|1843177137}}.\n* Winseck, Dwayne R.; Pike, Robert M., ''Communication and Empire'', Duke University Press, 2007 {{ISBN|9780822389996}}.\n* Whitelaw, ''Whitelaw's Telegraph Cyphers'', London: Whitelaw's Telegraph Cypher Co., 1904 {{oclc|820084531}}.\n\n[[Category:History of the telegraph]]\n[[Category:History of telecommunications in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:General Post Office]]\n", "name_user": "Spinningspark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography:fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_telegraphy_in_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Rhett discography", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist discography\n|Artist        = [[Thomas Rhett]]\n|Image         = Thomas Rhett.jpg\n|Caption       = Thomas Rhett performing in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], on January 24, 2013\n|Studio        = 4\n|Compilation   = \n|Live          = \n|EP            = 1\n|Singles       = 20 <!-- Beer Can't Fix -->\n|Music videos  = 22\n}}\n\nAmerican singer and songwriter [[Thomas Rhett]] has released four studio albums, one extended play and twenty singles, including two as a featured artist. His debut album, ''[[It Goes Like This]]'', debuted in the top 10 of the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] in 2013 and produced three number one singles on the [[Country Airplay|''Billboard'' Country Airplay]] chart. Rhett released his second album ''[[Tangled Up (Thomas Rhett album)|Tangled Up]]'' in 2015, which peaked at number six on the ''Billboard'' 200. Four of the album's five singles reached number one on the country charts, while the second single, \"[[Die a Happy Man]]\" became his first [[crossover (music)|crossover]] success and highest-charting single on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. His third album, ''[[Life Changes (Thomas Rhett album)|Life Changes]]'', was released in 2017 and includes the chart-topping single \"[[Craving You]]\". Twelve of Rhett's singles have received at least a Gold [[RIAA certification|certification]] from the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), with seven going Platinum.\n\nRhett has also written songs for other country artists, and made history in 2013 when half of the top 10 singles on the Country Airplay chart were written by Rhett or his father, [[Rhett Akins]], including the singer's own chart-topping hit, \"[[It Goes Like This (song)|It Goes Like This]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Conaway|first1=Alanna|title=Thomas Rhett and Rhett Akins Make Chart History As Family Is Responsible for Writing Half of the Top 10|url=http://www.roughstock.com/blog/thomas-rhett-and-rhett-akins-make-chart-history-as-family-is-responsible-for-writing-half-of-the-top-10|accessdate=September 6, 2017|work=Roughstock|publisher=Cheri Media|date=September 17, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102064612/http://www.roughstock.com/blog/thomas-rhett-and-rhett-akins-make-chart-history-as-family-is-responsible-for-writing-half-of-the-top-10|archivedate=November 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Studio albums ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Details\n! colspan=\"5\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:9em;\"| Sales\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| [[Music recording sales certifications|Certifications]]\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! style=\"width:4em;\"| [[Top Country Albums|US Country]]<br><ref name=\"Country Albums\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/music/thomas-rhett/chart-history/country-albums |title=Thomas Rhett Chart History (Top Country Albums) |publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=October 23, 2017}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:4em;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br><ref name=\"Billboard 200\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/music/thomas-rhett/chart-history/billboard-200 |title=Thomas Rhett Chart History (''Billboard'' 200) |publisher=Billboard |accessdate=October 23, 2017}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:4em;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br><ref>Peak positions on Australian Albums chart:\n* All except noted: {{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Thomas+Rhett|title=australian-charts.com \u2013 Discography Thomas Rhett|website=australian-charts.com|accessdate=September 22, 2017}}\n* ''Tangled Up'': {{cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/aria-albums-parkway-drive-ire-is-australias-no-1-album-20151003|title=ARIA Albums: Parkway Drive 'Ire' Is Australia's No 1 Album|publisher=Noise11|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|date=October 3, 2015|accessdat